  <section|What is a LLM Agent?>

  We give an informal definition for LLM agent:

  <\framed>
    <\infodef>
      A LLM agent is defined as:

      <\equation*>
        <text|Agent>=<text|Context (Memory)>+<text|LLMs (Base Model)>+<text|Tool Use (Skills)>.
      </equation*>
    </infodef>
  </framed>

  In practice, we can also classify LLM agents into therapy agent, service agent, coding agent<text-dots> We will focus mostly on coding agent in this short lecture. However, we take a Customer Service Agent as our first example by its simplicity.

  <\example>
    <\with|font-series|bold>
      (Customer Service Agent)
    </with>

    <\itemize>
      <item>Context: Product Manual. New Employee Training Manual<text-dots>

      <item>LLMs: Any LLMs..

      <item>Tool Use: call transfer, web link<text-dots>
    </itemize>
  </example>

  <\framed>
    <\infodef>
      <dueto|Long-term Memory>

      <\equation*>
        <text|Long-term Memory>=<text|Context Window>=<text|Input Token Limit>
      </equation*>

      <\equation*>
        1.5 <text|Token>\<approx\>1 Word
      </equation*>
    </infodef>
  </framed>

  <\folded>
    <\question>
      <label|question:long-context-forgetting>What's gonna happen if we put an entire Product Manual as a context? Will the LLM behave properly?
    </question>
  <|folded>
    <\answer>
      No, the LLM will forget most of the contents!\ 
    </answer>
  </folded>

  <\example>
    <with|font-series|bold|(Claude Code)>

    <\itemize>
      <item>Context: Code, Documents, <em|System Prompts>

      <item>LLMs: By default Claude Sonnet & Opus. By using <em|Claude Code Router>, one can apply any LLM through keys.

      <item>Tool: Shell command
    </itemize>
  </example>

  <\example>
    <with|font-series|bold|(Cline, Copilot, Trae, Cursor)>

    <\itemize>
      <item>Context: Code, Documents, <em|System Prompts>

      <item>LLMs: Any LLMs

      <item>Tool: Shell command (through VSCode, unstable, failed sometimes!), VSCode commands
    </itemize>
  </example>

  <\folded>
    <\question>
      Claude Code and Cursor can use the same model, why the price is different?
    </question>
  <|folded>
    <\answer>
      Claude code uses more token <math|\<Longleftarrow\>> Claude code has longer workflow & Claude code requires more contents!
    </answer>
  </folded>

