  <\remark>
    For a more tutorials on shell commands and command line tools, I highly recommend the <em|Missing Semester> Course provided by MIT: <hlink|https://missing.csail.mit.edu/|https://missing.csail.mit.edu/>
  </remark>

  <big-figure|<image|<tuple|<#>|/Users/jackyansongli/Desktop/Screenshot 2026-04-09 at 13.05.01.png>|0.4par|||>|Terminal (Physical)>

  <\folded>
    <\question>
      What is the difference between shell, terminal, terminal emulator, TUI, and GUI?
    </question>
  <|folded>
    <\answer>
      <\session|llm|DeepSeek>
        \;

        <\folded-io-text>
          \<gtr\>\ 
        <|folded-io-text>
          What is the difference between shell, terminal, terminal emulator, TUI, and GUI? answer in short words
        <|folded-io-text>
          <section*|Shell, Terminal, Terminal Emulator, TUI, and GUI><label|shell-terminal-terminal-emulator-tui-and-gui>

          <subsection*|Shell><label|shell>

          A shell is a command-line program that interprets user commands and communicates with the operating system to execute them. It acts as an interface between the user and the OS kernel. Common examples are Bash, Zsh, and PowerShell.\ 

          <subsection*|Terminal><label|terminal>

          Historically, a terminal was a physical hardware device (like a teletype or video terminal) used to input commands to and display output from a mainframe or minicomputer. In modern usage, it often refers to the text-based interface concept itself.\ 

          <subsection*|Terminal Emulator><label|terminal-emulator>

          A terminal emulator is a software application that replicates the function of a physical terminal within a graphical desktop environment. Examples include GNOME Terminal, Konsole, and iTerm2. It provides the window where you interact with a shell.\ 

          <subsection*|TUI (Text User Interface)><label|tui-text-user-interface>

          A TUI is an application interface that uses text and simple graphical elements (like boxes and menus) drawn with characters to provide interactive controls within a terminal environment. Examples include <with|font-family|tt|vim>, <with|font-family|tt|htop>, and <with|font-family|tt|ncdu>.\ 

          <subsection*|GUI (Graphical User Interface)><label|gui-graphical-user-interface>

          A GUI is a visual interface that uses windows, icons, menus, and a pointer (WIMP) for user interaction. It relies on a graphical display server and allows direct manipulation of graphical elements. Examples include modern desktop environments like Windows, macOS, and GNOME.\ 

          <subsection*|Core Relationship><label|core-relationship>

          A user typically runs a <with|font-series|bold|terminal emulator> (a GUI application) to open a <with|font-series|bold|terminal> window. Inside this window, a <with|font-series|bold|shell> (command interpreter) runs, accepting commands. A user might run a <with|font-series|bold|TUI> application (like a text editor) within this shell. All of this happens within the broader <with|font-series|bold|GUI> of the operating system's desktop.\ 
        </folded-io-text>

        <\input-text>
          \<gtr\>\ 
        <|input-text>
          \;
        </input-text>
      </session>
    </answer>
  </folded>

  <subsection|Shell command>

  See <hlink|Missing Semester Lecture 1|https://missing.csail.mit.edu/2020/course-shell/>. Most common shell “languages” are:

  <\itemize>
    <item>Windows: Command Prompt, Powershell, Elvish.

    <item>MacOS: Zsh, Elvish.

    <item>Linux: Zsh, Bash, Fish, Elvish.
  </itemize>

  (Bash) Shell command includes make folder: <verbatim|mkdir>, print working directory: <verbatim|pwd>, list contents in the current working directory: <verbatim|ls>, etc

