  <section|Memory is all you need, use OpenClaw>

  <subsection|OpenClaw workspace>

  OpenClaw stores its memory on <verbatim|~/.openclaw/workspace>.\ 

  <\itemize>
    <item><verbatim|Heartbeat.md>

    <item><verbatim|SOUL.md>

    <item><verbatim|IDENTITY.md>

    <item><math|\<vdots\>>
  </itemize>

  <subsection|Install OpenClaw!>

  <\hde>
    Install OpenClaw on Windows or macOS

    <\itemize>
      <item>for macOS: <verbatim|curl -fsSL https://openclaw.ai/install.sh \| bash>
    </itemize>

    During the installation, please choose moonshot and use <verbatim|kimi k2.5> API with <verbatim|mooonshot.cn> platform. No skills are required. If you have a Feishu account, you can also install the feishu skill.

    Some Windows users may encounter issue on installation, there is a serious bug on Windows for the new version of OpenClaw, please follow

    <\enumerate>
      <item><code*|npm -g uninstall openclaw>

      <item><code*|npm -g install openclaw@2026.4.2>

      <item><code*|openclaw onboard --install-daemon>

      <item><code*|openclaw gateway --port 18789 --verbose>
    </enumerate>

    to install an earlier version of OpenClaw.
  </hde>

  <\hde>
    Configure OpenClaw so you can use it on Liii STEM. Follow the instruction on <hlink|https://h02wf0jq8yp.feishu.cn/wiki/BpWFwLUttin0w7keHcpcsBiOnIe|https://h02wf0jq8yp.feishu.cn/wiki/BpWFwLUttin0w7keHcpcsBiOnIe>, The instruction is in Chinese, you can use translation tools.
  </hde>

  <\hde>
    Ask OpenClaw to read <math|> <verbatim|schrodinger.tmu> and memorize the format of <verbatim|.tmu>. Also ask him where he stored his memory.
  </hde>

  <\hde>
    Now, OpenClaw should be able to create <verbatim|.tmu> files by his own. Choose whatever topics you want and work with him to create a short report. If you have no idea, you can also choose from the following topics:

    <\itemize>
      <item>A short tutorial on Quantum mechanics.

      <item>A short tutorial on Linear regression.

      <item>A short tutorial on Machine Learning.
    </itemize>
  </hde>

