  <new-page>

  <appendix|ReAct Architecture (Optional)>

  <subsection|Workflow (Optional)>

  An LLM coding agent is an autonomous system that executes programming tasks end-to-end, while an LLM workflow is a structured sequence of steps, often involving human oversight, to guide an LLM toward a specific outcome.\ 

  <paragraph|Workflow products:>

  <\itemize>
    <item>Dify (1 year free for university student, web-based).

    <item>LangChain (require manual coding).
  </itemize>

  <subsection|ReAct v.s. workflow>

  <paragraph|What is ReAct?>

  <with|font-series|bold|ReAct (Reason + Act)> is a method for AI agents to solve problems by mimicking human thought:\ 

  <\enumerate>
    <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Reason:> Think step-by-step about what to do next.

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Act:> Use a tool (like Search or an API) to do it.

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Observe:> See the result.
  </enumerate>

  This loop repeats until the problem is solved. It's dynamic and flexible.\ 

  <with|font-series|bold|Example:>\ 

  <\itemize>
    <item><with|font-series|bold|Thought:> “I need the capital of France.”

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Act:> <with|font-family|tt|Search("capital of France")>

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Observe:> “Paris.”

    <item><with|font-series|bold|Answer:> “The capital is Paris.”
  </itemize>

  <hrule>

  <paragraph|ReAct vs.<nbsp>Workflow: The Key Difference>

  <tabular|<tformat|<twith|table-hmode|min>|<twith|table-width|1par>|<cwith|1|-1|1|-1|cell-hyphen|t>|<cwith|2|-1|2|-1|cell-tborder|1ln>|<cwith|2|-1|2|-1|cell-bborder|1ln>|<cwith|2|-1|2|-1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|2|-1|2|-1|cell-rborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|1|1|-1|cell-tborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|1|1|-1|cell-bborder|1ln>|<cwith|2|2|1|-1|cell-tborder|1ln>|<cwith|1|1|1|1|cell-tborder|0ln>|<cwith|5|5|1|1|cell-bborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-lborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-rborder|1ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-lborder|1ln>|<cwith|1|1|3|3|cell-tborder|0ln>|<cwith|5|5|3|3|cell-bborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-lborder|1ln>|<cwith|1|-1|2|2|cell-rborder|1ln>|<cwith|1|-1|3|3|cell-rborder|0ln>|<cwith|1|1|2|-1|cell-background|light grey>|<cwith|1|-1|1|1|cell-background|light grey>|<cwith|5|5|1|-1|cell-vmode|exact>|<cwith|6|6|1|-1|cell-vmode|exact>|<cwith|5|5|1|-1|cell-height|29709tmpt>|<cwith|6|6|1|-1|cell-height|31106tmpt>|<table|<row|<\cell>
    \;
  </cell>|<\cell>
    <strong|ReAct>
  </cell>|<\cell>
    <strong|Workflow (e.g., Zapier)>
  </cell>>|<row|<\cell>
    <strong|Nature>
  </cell>|<\cell>
    <strong|Dynamic.> Figures out the path as it goes.
  </cell>|<\cell>
    <strong|Static.> Follows a pre-defined path.
  </cell>>|<row|<\cell>
    <strong|Decision>
  </cell>|<\cell>
    Makes decisions <strong|in real-time> based on reasoning.
  </cell>|<\cell>
    All decisions are <strong|pre-programmed> (if/else).
  </cell>>|<row|<\cell>
    <strong|Best For>
  </cell>|<\cell>
    Open-ended, complex tasks (research, analysis).
  </cell>|<\cell>
    Repetitive, predictable tasks (send email on form submit).
  </cell>>|<row|<\cell>
    <strong|Analogy>
  </cell>|<\cell>
    A <strong|Human Assistant> you give a goal to.
  </cell>|<\cell>
    A <strong|Factory Robot> on an assembly line.
  </cell>>|<row|<\cell>
    <with|font-series|bold|Products>
  </cell>|<\cell>
    Claude Code
  </cell>|<\cell>
    Dify
  </cell>>>>>

  <with|font-series|bold|In short:> ReAct <em|figures out> the steps, a Workflow <em|follows> the steps.\ 

  <\session|llm|DeepSeek>
    <\folded-io-text>
      \<gtr\>\ 
    <|folded-io-text>
      introduceme ReAct, and what is the difference between react and workflow
    <|folded-io-text>
      <section*|ReAct: Reasoning and Acting for LLM Agents><label|react-reasoning-and-acting-for-llm-agents>

      <subsection*|Introduction to ReAct><label|introduction-to-react>

      ReAct (Reasoning + Acting) is a framework for building LLM agents that combines <with|font-series|bold|chain-of-thought reasoning> with <with|font-series|bold|action execution> in an interactive loop. The agent alternates between generating reasoning traces (thinking steps) and performing actions (like API calls, tool usage, or environment interactions) to solve complex tasks.\ 

      <subsubsection*|Core Concept><label|core-concept>

      ReAct enables an LLM to:\ 

      <\enumerate>
        <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Reason> internally about what to do next

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Act> upon the environment or tools

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Observe> the results

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Repeat> until the task is complete
      </enumerate>

      This creates a dynamic loop: <with|font-family|tt|Thought \<rightarrow\> Action \<rightarrow\> Observation \<rightarrow\> Thought \<rightarrow\> ...>\ 

      <subsubsection*|Key Components><label|key-components>

      <\itemize>
        <item><with|font-series|bold|Thought>: The LLM's internal reasoning about the current situation and next steps

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Action>: Executable steps (tool calls, API requests, code execution)

        <item><with|font-series|bold|Observation>: Results from the action that inform subsequent reasoning
      </itemize>

      <subsection*|ReAct vs.<nbsp>Workflow: Key Differences><label|react-vs.-workflow-key-differences>

      <subsubsection*|Nature of Execution><label|nature-of-execution>

      <with|font-series|bold|ReAct> is fundamentally <with|font-series|bold|agentic and autonomous>. The LLM drives the process, deciding what to do next based on its reasoning and previous observations. The path isn't predetermined.\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|Workflow> is <with|font-series|bold|procedural and structured>. It follows a predefined sequence of steps, often with specific handoffs between different components or human checkpoints.\ 

      <subsubsection*|Decision-Making><label|decision-making>

      In <with|font-series|bold|ReAct>, decision-making is <with|font-series|bold|emergent and adaptive>. The agent can change course based on what it discovers during execution.\ 

      In a <with|font-series|bold|workflow>, decision-making is <with|font-series|bold|predefined and rule-based>. The flow is determined in advance, with limited branching based on conditions.\ 

      <subsubsection*|Human Involvement><label|human-involvement>

      <with|font-series|bold|ReAct> typically operates <with|font-series|bold|autonomously> once started, though it can be designed to request human input when stuck.\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|Workflows> often include <with|font-series|bold|explicit human-in-the-loop> stages for review, approval, or decision points.\ 

      <subsubsection*|Flexibility vs.<nbsp>Reliability><label|flexibility-vs.-reliability>

      <with|font-series|bold|ReAct> offers <with|font-series|bold|high flexibility> for novel or unpredictable tasks but may have <with|font-series|bold|variable reliability> depending on the LLM's reasoning quality.\ 

      <with|font-series|bold|Workflows> provide <with|font-series|bold|high reliability and consistency> for repetitive tasks but have <with|font-series|bold|limited flexibility> for handling edge cases not anticipated in the design.\ 

      <subsection*|Practical Example><label|practical-example>

      <subsubsection*|ReAct Approach for “Get today's weather in Tokyo”><label|react-approach-for-get-todays-weather-in-tokyo>

      <\code>
        Thought: I need to find today's weather in Tokyo. First, I should get the current date.

        Action: Get current date

        Observation: Date is 2024-01-15

        Thought: Now I need to call a weather API for Tokyo on this date.

        Action: Call weather API with location=Tokyo, date=2024-01-15

        Observation: Weather data: Sunny, 22°C

        Thought: I have the answer.

        Action: Return result: "Tokyo weather on 2024-01-15: Sunny, 22°C"
      </code>

      <subsubsection*|Workflow Approach for the Same Task><label|workflow-approach-for-the-same-task>

      <\enumerate>
        <assign|labelenumi|<macro|<number|<enumi-nr>|arabic>.>>

        <item>Step 1: System automatically gets current date

        <item>Step 2: System calls weather API with Tokyo and date parameters

        <item>Step 3: System formats the API response

        <item>Step 4: (Optional) Human reviews the formatted output

        <item>Step 5: System delivers the final result
      </enumerate>

      <subsection*|When to Use Each><label|when-to-use-each>

      <subsubsection*|Use ReAct When:><label|use-react-when>

      <\itemize>
        <item>Tasks require complex reasoning and planning

        <item>The solution path isn't known in advance

        <item>You need adaptability to unexpected situations

        <item>You're exploring or prototyping solutions
      </itemize>

      <subsubsection*|Use Workflows When:><label|use-workflows-when>

      <\itemize>
        <item>Tasks follow a predictable, repeatable pattern

        <item>Consistency and reliability are critical

        <item>Regulatory or compliance requirements demand specific steps

        <item>Human oversight at specific points is necessary

        <item>The process is well-understood and stable
      </itemize>

      <subsection*|Hybrid Approaches><label|hybrid-approaches>

      Many practical systems combine both paradigms:\ 

      <\itemize>
        <item>Using <with|font-series|bold|workflows> to structure the overall process

        <item>Embedding <with|font-series|bold|ReAct agents> within specific steps where adaptive reasoning is needed

        <item>Having agents trigger workflow steps when appropriate
      </itemize>

      This combination leverages the reliability of workflows with the adaptability of agentic reasoning where it provides the most value.\ 
    </folded-io-text>

